In simple terms, **Helmet.js** is a collection of 11 smaller middleware functions that set **HTTP response headers** to secure your Express app.

When a browser (like Chrome) talks to your server, the server sends back "headers"â€”hidden instructions that tell the browser how to behave. By default, Express reveals sensitive information and allows certain risky behaviors. Helmet fixes this.

---

### The 3 Most Important Things Helmet Does:

#### 1. Hiding Your Identity (`x-powered-by`)

By default, Express tells the world: *"Hi, I am a server running on Express."* Hackers use this to look for version-specific bugs. Helmet removes this header so attackers don't know what technology you are using.

#### 2. Preventing XSS (`Content-Security-Policy`)

This is the most powerful part of Helmet. It sets a **CSP (Content Security Policy)**.

* **Without Helmet:** A hacker could inject a malicious `<script>` into your "TimeGlass" review section. The browser would run it and potentially steal the user's login cookie.
* **With Helmet:** The header tells the browser: *"Only execute scripts that come from my own domain (timeglass.vercel.app)."* The browser will block the hacker's script.

#### 3. Preventing Clickjacking (`X-Frame-Options`)

Clickjacking is when a hacker puts your website (like your "TaskFlow" app) inside a transparent `<iframe>` on their own site. They trick users into clicking a button on your app while they think they are clicking something else.
Helmet sets headers that tell the browser: *"Do not allow this site to be put in an iframe."*

---

### How it looks in your Code

Since you have it on your resume, you likely implemented it like this in your `server.js` or `app.js`:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const helmet = require('helmet');

const app = express();

// This one line enables 11 different security headers
app.use(helmet()); 

```

